1.1 DataSources

1.1.1 PanCan Atlas

https://gdc.cancer.gov/about-data/publications/pancanatlas

1.1.2 GDCâ€”Workflow and Normalization

GDC gives very explicit details about their pipelines, including the actual code.

  • RNASeq: https://docs.gdc.cancer.gov/Data/Bioinformatics_Pipelines/Expression_mRNA_Pipeline/
  • MAF: https://docs.gdc.cancer.gov/Data/File_Formats/MAF_Format/

More information and data types, sources, and processing is in the Data Dictionary.

Itâ€™s clear from the description and flowchart that the GDC pipeline does not do any normalization other than within sample FPKM and upper quantile normalized FPKM. Details are given the the pages linked to above. These are the values in the RNASeq file mentioned above. Still, as shown below, the across-sample data has a fairly consistent range. This suggests either incredible attention to detail in every step from processing samples to sequencing, or something else that I have not found documented yet.

The GDC Data Portal is another source for data. The link they have for a description of the data links to the data dictionary described above.

1.1.3 TCGA

This GDC page on the TCGA Pan-Cancer project links to some additional resources

1.1.4 ISB-CGC

ISB-CGC hosts the raw data from GDC and other project in multiple formats, including BigQuery tables. This is actually where I am drawing data for this analysis.

I communicated with ISB-CGC.

We have an exhaustive ETL process that does that huge manifest / download from the GDC portal. Weâ€™ve also got the Pancancer Atlas data in BQ format in our isb-cgc-bq.pancancer_atlas dataset

1.2.2 Mutations

This table is somewhat like a VCF file. It lists somatic mutations found in tumor samples and has annotated these with gene symbols, various variant classifications, and other information. Based on the Variant_Classifiction column, we will select only genes/regions that have coding consequencesâ€”i.e.Â are code for amino acids critical for downstream pathways.

This comes straight from the ISB-CGC maintained tables of the TCGA data.

Selecting the project KIRC.

NOTE: We are only interested in the barcodes for tumor samples

proj_short_name = glue("TCGA-KIRC")

if(load_from_bq)
{

1.2.4 Combined table

For downstream analysis we join the MAF and RNASeq tables on the gene symobls and sample barcodes.

Question: Were the sample/gene pairs in the MAF table processed the same way as the ones not in the MAF table?

Question: Do we presume sample/gene pairs not in the MAF table do not have mutations? That would seem odd, since these are all tumor samples.

NOTE: we are adding a variable gene_mutation_type that captures whether that sample is or is not included in the MAF file. That is, were somatic mutations called for that sample.

1.2.4.1 Samples in MAF vs RNASeq Tables

mutation_barcodes = 
  mutations %>% 
  pull(sample_barcode) %>% 
  unique()

rnaseq_barcodes = 
  rnaseq_counts %>% 
  pull(sample_barcode) %>% 
  unique()

1.2.4.3 Join the Tables

if (load_from_bq)
{
  counts_and_mutations = 
  
    ### Left join to keep all genes with rnaseq counts, even if they
    ### don't show up in the MAF table.
    full_join(
      
      rnaseq_counts %>% 
        mutate(in_rnaseq_table = T),
      
      ### Add column to remember source of gene-sample pair
      mutations %>%
        mutate(in_maf_table = T),
      
      by = c("gene_symbol", "sample_barcode"),
      
      suffix = c(".maf", ".rnaseq")
      
    ) %>%
    
    mutate(
      ### Because we perform a left join into the rnaseq table,
      ### sample/gene pairs not in the MAF table will be NA.
      ### change to Not In MAF Table
      in_maf_table = ifelse(is.na(in_maf_table), F, T),
      in_rnaseq_table = ifelse(is.na(in_rnaseq_table), F, T),
      maf_only = ifelse(in_maf_table & !in_rnaseq_table, T, F),
      rnaseq_only = ifelse(in_rnaseq_table & !in_maf_table, T, F),
      gene_mutation_type = ifelse(in_maf_table, "Mutant", "Wildtype"),
      variant_classification = ifelse(is.na(variant_classification), "Wildtype", variant_classification)
    ) %>% 
    
    filter(sample_barcode %in% mutation_barcodes) 
  
  write.fst(counts_and_mutations, path="large_files/KIRC-counts_and_mutations.fst", compress=100)
} else
{
  counts_and_mutations = read.fst(path="large_files/KIRC-counts_and_mutations.fst")
}

1.4.3 Observations

  1. The quantile boxes (25%, median, 75%) across samples look very comparable. I would definitely have not expected this with raw counts. I need to examine the TCGA workflow outlines carefully to see if some kind of normalization was done prior to the HTSeq step.

  2. The counts for genes in both the MAF table vs.Â those not in the MAF table look quite different. As shown below, in both cases, the medians of the RNASeq table only genes are statistically significantly lower.

1.5.1.1 Calculate Descriptive Statsâ€”Mutant vs.Â Wildtype

sample_wise_descriptive_stats =
  counts_and_mutations %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("HTSeq"),
    names_to = "counts_type",
    values_to = "counts"
  ) %>% 
  group_by(sample_barcode, gene_mutation_type, counts_type) %>% 
    summarize(
      Min = min(counts),
      Q1 = quantile(counts, 0.25, na.rm=T),
      Median = median(counts, na.rm=T),
      Mean = mean(counts, na.rm=T),
      SD = sd(counts, na.rm=T),
      Var = var(counts, na.rm=T),
      Q3 = quantile(counts, 0.75, na.rm=T),
      Max = max(counts),
      IQR = Q3 - Q1
    ) %>% 
  arrange(Max) %>% 
  tail(-1) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ungroup()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'sample_barcode', 'gene_mutation_type'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

1.5.3 Gene-Wiseâ€”Plots

1.5.3.1 Calculate Descriptive Statsâ€”Mutant vs.Â Wildtype

gene_wise_descriptive_stats =
  counts_and_mutations %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("HTSeq"),
    names_to = "counts_type",
    values_to = "counts"
  ) %>% 
  group_by(gene_symbol, gene_mutation_type, counts_type) %>% 
    summarize(
      Min = min(counts),
      Q1 = quantile(counts, 0.25, na.rm=T),
      Median = median(counts, na.rm=T),
      Mean = mean(counts, na.rm=T),
      SD = sd(counts, na.rm=T),
      Var = var(counts, na.rm=T),
      Q3 = quantile(counts, 0.75, na.rm=T),
      Max = max(counts),
      IQR = Q3 - Q1
    ) %>% 
  arrange(Max) %>% 
  tail(-1) %>% 
  ungroup()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'gene_symbol', 'gene_mutation_type'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
